-- Rework responses to be concurrent
-- Responses should be created by the command disbatcher and not the command itself
-- Responses should contain the sender's name
-- The sender should receiver a confirmation from the receiver that the command is being processed, otherwise it will time out after 5 seconds
-- After receiving the confirmation, the sender will reset the timeout to 20 seconds
-- A keepalive response may be sent to the sender to reset the timeout to a specific amount
-- Keepalive responses will be ignored by the sender if the command has already timed out
-- Responses should accumulate data and only send when flushed
-- Responses should keep track of time between messages for use in presentation to sender
-- Sender should delay printing of response messages based on time since last message
-- Responses should be closed with either a 'completed' call or a 'failed' message
-- Failure to provide either a success or failure state will result in a timeout
-- Command timeouts are purely for the user's benefit, and will not prevent the receiver from continuing to execute the command
-- A timeout means that the command is removed from the senders buffer, and the user can consider that command to have failed
-- A timeout does not prevent the receiver from continuing to execute the command and send responses if the command did not actually fail

